{"cursor":"19089","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = name = Charles Cruft honorific_suffix = image =\n| Charlescruft.jpg image_size = 200px alt = caption = A photograph of Charles\n| Cruft, published in 1902 birth_name = birth_date = birth_place = death_date =\n| death_place = Highbury, London, England death_cause = Myocardial infarction\n| resting_place = Highgate Cemetery resting_place_coordinates = monuments =\n| residence = nationality = British education = alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* Ardingly College,Sussex\n* Birkbeck College, London }}\n| occupation = Show promoter and businessman years_active = known_for = Crufts\n| Dog Show influenced = Conformation showing home_town = net_worth = Â£30476 9s\n| 3d religion =  denomination =  spouse = {{Plainlist|\n* Charlotte Hutchinson (first wife)\n* Emma Isabel Hartshorn (second wife) }}\n| children = Charles Francis, Louise, Cecil Arthur and Clara Helen Grace (from\n| first marriage) parents = Charles Cruft (father) awards = signature =\n| signature_alt = signature_size =\n}} 'Charles Alfred Cruft' (28 June 1852 â 10 September 1938) was a British\nshowman who founded the Crufts dog show. Charles first became involved with dogs\nwhen he began to work at Spratt's, a manufacturer of dog biscuits. He rose to\nthe position of General Manager, and whilst working for Spratt's in France he\nwas invited to run his first dog show at the 1878 Exposition Universelle. After\nrunning dog shows in London for four years, he ran his first Cruft's dog show in\n1891, and continued to run a further 45 shows until his death in 1938, as well\nas running two cat shows in 1894 and 1895. He was involved in a range of dog\nbreed clubs, including that for Schipperkes, Pugs and Borzois. He and his wife\nupheld a story that they never owned a dog, and instead owned a cat, however\nCruft admitted to owning at least one Saint Bernard in his memoirs, published\nposthumously.\n","linknr":317,"